Neutrons in the energy range 12.5 to 19.6 MeV
were produced with an absorbed titanium-tritium target
by using 15 different emerging angles. The tritium
target was a 3 mg/cm2 T-Ti layer on a 4 cm diameter by
0.3 mm thick silver sheet, cooled by a thin water
.The neutron spectrum effective at each sample was cal-
culated using a MONTE-CARLO code based on the kine-
Activation technique in combination with high-
resolution gamma-ray spectroscopy was used to measure
the activity from the Y-90m, Nb-92m, Cs-136 and Hf-181
products, as well as the Na-24 monitor activity.
The Y-90g product was radiochemically separated
and the beta- activity was counted.
A 35 cm3 Ge(Li) detector was used for the gamma
measurements, while beta-ray counting was employed for
the beta emitter Y-90g. The latter measurement was
started about 30 hours after the end of the
irradiation, in order to have complete decay of Y-90m.
A proton recoil telescope, placed at an angle
of 16 degrees and a distance of 80 cm from the neutron
source was used to measure the neutron fluence.
.A weighted average of these two fluence monitors was
used. The values agreed in general within 5 percent.
.The samples consisted of 2 cm diameter by 0.5 cm thick
discs of metal or oxide powder, pressed at a pressure
of 18 tons/cm2. The purities were for Nb g.t. 99.5
percent, for Ta g.t. 99.7 percent, while the La sample
was the compound La2O3 of technical quality. The
samples were sandwiched between two aluminium sheets,
2 cm in diameter by 0.1 cm thick. The distance from
the source to the sample middle plane was 7.8 cm.
Irradiations were performed for 40 to 67 hours.
.The gamma count rates were corrected for self-absorp-
tion, pile up, coincidence loss, geometry, efficiency
of the detector and gamma-ray abundance. The beta
